As yet it is uncertain whether there will be a second tale. Diz is both a construct and a psuedonym -  Should there be another though. It will certainly be another great addition to the Beatnpress library.
When the notes and discarded manuscripts were found they were edited and spliced together in yet another inspirational cut up style  creating a completely new and original narrative.
The tale is also the result of twenty years of discarded ideas and notes that have never been published before.
Using poetry, prose, screenwriting, images and other creative elements it generates an almost fragmented trip into both reality and the fantastical that serves to echo its contents.

"A highly entertaining lysergic flight of fantasy across the astral planes. An energetic rollercoaster of voodoo, jazz, Jim Morrison and the power of spirituality. As inventive and as original as a solo by the master himself, Dizzy Gillespie.”
The layered approach allows the reader to enter the realms that are created. As fellow author Jason Brummell, ( All About My Girl and All Or Nothing) says - it is

It's novel approach creates a  tale that is modern, yet has enough familiarity in it that it is still entertaining.  There is in fact a point where the novel explores the ideas of clichés and whether both the book and the protagonist needs to use them.
This book has themes running through it, ideas that are interesting tangents, and distractions, yet will return to its main theme. Much like the improvisation you would find in Jazz music.

The Lost Notes by Diz is a book that sees the author approach his topic in a creative form that is- well - not typical.  There is an affinity for Jazz in the creation of the novel - but not in the long unpunctuated style and rhythms of the original Beat writer, Jack Kerouac. No.
Creating something that is both original and different is no easy task these days.  It can sometimes feel like everything has been done before, and to some degree that is true.
